<p class="p">We follow a Bayesian version of the penalised spline approach [
 <xref rid="pone.0213300.ref016" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">16</xref>, 
 <xref rid="pone.0213300.ref017" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">17</xref>] so as to learn about the first-digit probability 
 <italic class="italic">
  <bold class="bold">p</bold>
  <sub class="sub">t</sub>
 </italic>. We assign a first-order random walk prior to the regression coefficients 
 <bold class="bold">
  <italic class="italic">β</italic>
 </bold>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub> = (
 <italic class="italic">β</italic>
 <sub class="sub">1,
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub>, …, 
 <italic class="italic">β</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">K</italic>+3,
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub>)
 <sup class="sup">T</sup>, which relate an independent and identical Gaussian error 
 <italic class="italic">ε</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub> with mean zero and variance 
 <inline-formula id="pone.0213300.e008" class="inline-formula">
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <graphic xlink:href="pone.0213300.e008.jpg" id="pone.0213300.e008g" mimetype="image" position="anchor" orientation="portrait" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   <math id="M8" class="math">
    <msubsup class="msubsup">
     <mi class="mi">τ</mi>
     <mi class="mi">d</mi>
     <mn class="mn">2</mn>
    </msubsup>
   </math>
  </alternatives>
 </inline-formula>, that is, 
 <disp-formula id="pone.0213300.e009" class="disp-formula">
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <graphic xlink:href="pone.0213300.e009.jpg" id="pone.0213300.e009g" mimetype="image" position="anchor" orientation="portrait" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   <math id="M9" class="math">
    <mtable displaystyle="true" class="mtable">
     <mtr class="mtr">
      <mtd columnalign="right" class="mtd">
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <msub class="msub">
         <mi class="mi">β</mi>
         <mrow class="mrow">
          <mi class="mi">d</mi>
          <mo class="mo">,</mo>
          <mi class="mi">k</mi>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo class="mo">=</mo>
        <msub class="msub">
         <mi class="mi">β</mi>
         <mrow class="mrow">
          <mi class="mi">d</mi>
          <mo class="mo">,</mo>
          <mi class="mi">k</mi>
          <mo class="mo">-</mo>
          <mn class="mn">1</mn>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo class="mo">+</mo>
        <msub class="msub">
         <mi class="mi">ε</mi>
         <mi class="mi">d</mi>
        </msub>
        <mo class="mo">,</mo>
        <mspace width="1.em" class="mspace"/>
        <msub class="msub">
         <mi class="mi">ε</mi>
         <mi class="mi">d</mi>
        </msub>
        <mo class="mo">∼</mo>
        <mi class="mi">N</mi>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <mo class="mo">(</mo>
         <mn class="mn">0</mn>
         <mo class="mo">,</mo>
         <msubsup class="msubsup">
          <mi class="mi">τ</mi>
          <mi class="mi">d</mi>
          <mn class="mn">2</mn>
         </msubsup>
         <mo class="mo">)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo class="mo">,</mo>
        <mspace width="1.em" class="mspace"/>
        <mi class="mi">k</mi>
        <mo class="mo">=</mo>
        <mn class="mn">2</mn>
        <mo class="mo">,</mo>
        <mo class="mo">…</mo>
        <mo class="mo">,</mo>
        <mi class="mi">K</mi>
        <mo class="mo">+</mo>
        <mn class="mn">3</mn>
        <mo class="mo">;</mo>
       </mrow>
      </mtd>
     </mtr>
    </mtable>
   </math>
  </alternatives>
  <label class="label">(6)</label>
 </disp-formula> a flat (uniform) prior is set for the initial coefficient 
 <italic class="italic">β</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>,1
 </sub>. The first order random walk prior can be represented in a matrix form, 
 <bold class="bold">
  <italic class="italic">Fβ</italic>
 </bold>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub> = 
 <italic class="italic">ε</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub>, where 
 <italic class="italic">ε</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub> is a (
 <italic class="italic">K</italic> + 2)-vector of 
 <italic class="italic">ε</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">d</italic>
 </sub>’s and 
 <bold class="bold">
  <italic class="italic">F</italic>
 </bold> is a difference matrix of dimension (
 <italic class="italic">K</italic> + 2, 
 <italic class="italic">K</italic> + 3). The 
 <bold class="bold">
  <italic class="italic">F</italic>
 </bold> has a diagonal of 1’s (
 <italic class="italic">i</italic> = 
 <italic class="italic">j</italic>), −1’s for the next elements to the diagonal (
 <italic class="italic">i</italic> = 
 <italic class="italic">j</italic> + 1), and zero otherwise for the (
 <italic class="italic">i</italic>, 
 <italic class="italic">j</italic>)th element with 
 <italic class="italic">i</italic> ∈ {1, …, 
 <italic class="italic">K</italic> + 2} and 
 <italic class="italic">j</italic> ∈ {1, …, 
 <italic class="italic">K</italic> + 3}.
</p>
